## Why This Is Asked
Microsoft tests understanding of tokenization trade-offs and attention mechanisms in multilingual contexts - critical for products like Bing Chat and Azure AI services.

## Expected Answer
Strong candidates discuss: 1) Byte-Pair Encoding with language-specific merges, 2) Vocabulary size vs token count trade-offs, 3) Adding language ID tokens, 4) Attention modifications like language-aware positional encoding or cross-lingual attention heads.

## Code Example
```typescript
// Custom tokenizer with language-aware merges
class MultilingualTokenizer {
  vocabulary: Map<string, number>
  languageMerges: Map<string, string[]>

  tokenize(text: string, lang: string): number[] {
    const tokens = []
    const merges = this.languageMerges.get(lang) || []
    // Apply language-specific BPE merges
    return this.applyBPE(text, merges)
  }
}

// Language-aware attention modification
class LanguageAwareAttention {
  forward(x: Tensor, langIds: Tensor): Tensor {
    const attention = this.multiHeadAttention(x)
    const langBias = this.getLanguageBias(langIds)
    return attention + langBias
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you handle rare characters or emojis in the vocabulary?
- What metrics would you use to evaluate tokenizer efficiency?
- How does this approach scale to 50+ languages?

## Why This Is Asked
Streaming generation with chunked inputs is common in real-time chat; understanding and controlling cross-chunk attention drift is essential for reliability, especially in multilingual contexts.

## Key Concepts
- Streaming/incremental generation and chunk boundaries
- Attention drift across chunks and languages
- Boundary-aware gating vs retraining
- Lightweight diagnostic pipelines and drift metrics (KL/JS)

## Code Example
```javascript
// Minimal example: compute per-head attention mass on current chunk
function headMass(attn, currentIdx, prevCount) {
  // attn: [heads][tokens][tokens]
  const heads = attn.length;
  const currentMass = [];
  for (let h = 0; h < heads; h++) {
    let sumAll = 0;
    let sumCurrent = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < attn[h].length; i++) {
      for (let j = 0; j < attn[h][i].length; j++) {
        sumAll += attn[h][i][j];
        if (i >= currentIdx - prevCount && i < currentIdx) {
          sumCurrent += attn[h][i][j];
        }
      }
    }
    currentMass.push(sumCurrent / (sumAll || 1));
  }
  return currentMass;
}
```

